It has been proposed in the documentary ‘Great Pyramid K 2019’ that the Ancient Egyptians
invented the metric system thousands of years before it was supposedly invented in Europe.
They needed to make measurements that relied on more than a king’s foot, because then the
unit would change from king to king, so they used water droplets, something they thought
universal and constant. They put a drop on a ﬂat surface and let gravity ﬂatten it out, and that
became their unit of measurement to make the what they called the cubit, which they used to
construct the pyramids, which the same people claim to coincide with the modern metric
system, and that it will always measure 1 cm.!
I thought is this true? Wouldn’t it depend on the size of the water droplet? So I made droplets
from two diﬀerent objects of diﬀerent sizes to produce diﬀerent size droplets. less it looks like
the two drops are indeed a cm in diameter.!
But they can’t have too much water or the the surface tension of the water won’s hold it
together, it well burst and water will ﬂow out. I think a condition is it has to be a circle no
lopsided like an egg. So you should use a round tip. I did pretty well with stick from a tree with
irregular tips though. Here are the photos:!
